### Using LODES to construct the experienced MW

Workplace location often differs with residence location. Thus, statutory MW 
doesn't capture relevant variation in changes in income at local level.

Construct residence-workplace ZIP code matrix using LODES data. Observe working 
population for each pair of zipcodes.

Denote ZIP codes by $i$ and monthly dates by $t$. 

- $\mathds{Z}_i$: set of ZIP codes in which $i$'s residents work (including $i$).
- $N_{iz}$ is the number of workers who reside in ZIP code $i$ and work in $z$
- $N_i$ total working-age population of ZIP code $i$.
- $\{\omega_{iz}\}_{z \in \mathds{Z}_i}$: share of workers who work in each location $z$ 
from $i$, defined as $$\omega_{iz} = \frac{N_{iz}}{N_i}$$

### The experienced MW

Let $\underline{w}_{it}$ be statutory MW in ZIP code $i$ and month $t$

Define the experienced minimum wage measure as:

\begin{equation}
	\underline{w}^{\text{exp}}_{it} = 
			\sum_{z \in \mathds{Z}_i} \omega_{iz} \underline{w}_{zt} \ . 
\end{equation}

Suppose a city without MW workers raises the MW, and MW workers live outside the 
city.

- The experienced MW will allow for the policy to spill over to those neighborhoods.

